metadata.name: blinksquare 2022 #116
metadata.description:
From the pixel-lab vault - evolved from 'blinksquare' (2008) 
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Mouse-click switches between:
- screen scaled image
- The large image (for printing)

Right-click: Save/Copy the image

A custom created 'soft' pixel 2D/3D engine,
written in vanilla JavaScript some more info in the source-code
- The work will refresh and restart after some time -
-------------------------------------------------

I created 'blinksquare' back in 2008 in Secondlife,
it was like a kinetic 3D sculpture; that would change over time.

I wanted to do a 2022 remake; and while working on it; it evolved a bit.
Also inspired by writing and ancient Hieroglyphs from around the world 


xxx Amsterdam chillout


For the love of Art, hugging someone you love, and filling that RGB-and Z buffer  ^__^

metadata.name: City Pop - AI Study II #220
metadata.description:
City Pop takes you to a lively and geometric city created by digital architects. The use of shapes, colors, and lines causes visionary hallucinations leading the viewer to imaginary places filled with endless possibilities.

This project is a generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow. The JavaScript code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #2 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: Haemo Globs #260
metadata.description:
The shape and function of haematids (red blood cells) has always fascinated me. Perhaps their mathematical smoothness and candy-like aspect resonated with me as a child. Their simple appearance distinguished them from the other cell types I had learned about. I imagined them engorged with sweet-flavoured oxygen and juicily popping under my bite.

I hope for this generative artwork to communicate my appreciation for these never-ending body travellers.

metadata.name: Overgrowth #17
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of random growth focused on three interconnected elements. The first is a randomly moving brush, the second is one is an alternating overlay of white and black circles along bezier points between brush movements, and the final one being a continually decreasing brush size.

The overall result gives a complex scribble art effect. 

Created with p5.js
